x4freetext: Prompt fission neutron multiplicity.
Time uncertainty 1.0-1.2 nsec ( ~3%).
Prompt neutron TOF spectra were measured at 11 angles
relative to direction of light fragment motion.
Two detectors ND1 and ND2 (50 x 50-mm and
40 x 60-mm stilbene crystals combined with a
Hamamatsu-R6091 photoelectric multiplier); placed at
an angle of 90deg with respect to each other at a
distance of ~50 cm from the 252-Cf source; shielded by
lead and polyethylene.
Used for prompt neutrons detection, detection threshold
Dependence of the detection efficiency on the neutron
energy was determined as the ratio of the integral
spectrum of prompt fission neutrons obtained by the
angular summation of the measured spectra to the
standard spectrum for  252Cf, multiplied by the average
total number of prompt fission neutrons 3.7610+-0.0051.
Low-pressure multi-wire plane proportional
detector (MPPD) was used as a start signal; placed at a
distance of 7 mm from the Cf source.
Stop MPPDs as two arcs of eight detectors on a
circle at 140mm distance fro the center of a chamber.
Working gas - isobutane at 5mbar pressure,
500 V voltage.
- the dependence of timing on the amplitude of signals;
- the difference between the times of flight of
heavy and light fragments;
- the difference in the efficiency of detection of
fission fragments for given angles;
- the contribution of prompt fission neutrons from
complementary (conjugated) fragment;
- the background of the neutron detector;
- the limited angular and energy resolutions;
- the dependence of the efficiency of the neutron
detector on the energy of the neutron;
- correction to the angular summation for determining
the integral spectrum because of discrete distribution
of the observables;
- the relativistic correction at the determination
of the neutron energy.
Measured data are compared with theoretical
model calculations - see formula (15) and Table 1
(parameters) in JET,125,(4),619,2017.
